equired, encrypt with a key derived from the passphrase itself (nested key derivation)\",\n    \"Encrypt sensitive spine state (focus session, health, credits) before storing in localStorage using the user's derived encryption key from HistoryOfThought\",\n    \"Sanitize all dynamic values inserted into style attributes; use CSS class names or validated numeric ranges instead\",\n    \"Add allowlist validation for courseCode parameter: validate against known institutional course codes before use\",\n    \"Use timing-safe comparison for passphrase validation if implemented server-side (Node.js crypto.timingSafeEqual)\",\n    \"Gate all console logging behind a debug flag; remove public-facing logging of auth events and state changes\",\n    \"Add Content Security Policy (CSP) headers to mitigate XSS if this app is served over HTTPS\"\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Findings Summary\n\n**Critical Issues:**\n1. **No real authentication** — localStorage flag can be spoofed in DevTools\n2. **Unsafe URL-based reset** — `?reset=true` wipes data without confirmation\n3. **LMS sync is client-side only** — no credential validation or OAuth flow\n\n**Design Trade-offs to Review:**\n- The \"sovereign\" local-first architecture is good for privacy, but localStorage secrets leak easily on shared devices\n- Salt + passphrase both in localStorage enables offline rainbow table attacks if the device is compromised\n- Focus/health/credits unencrypted in localStorage are visible to browser extensions and DevTools\n\n**Immediate Actions:**\n1. Move all auth state to memory (in-memory session object, not localStorage)\n2. Remove or require confirmation for `?reset=true`\n3. Implement actual OAuth 2.0 for LMS sync, or remove the feature\n",
